{"source_key":"sha256-9aeddc9533856b773c893728ead17d15","record_index":82,"record_hash":"sha256:1fac910a611047ae221bf15a59aa910b87b03ee5e35836875189f1df352a947f","timestamp":"2026-05-13T13:19:11.311Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. Use `gix::Repository::find_remote()` and then read the remote’s fetch refspecs:\n\n```rust\nuse gix::remote::Direction;\n\nlet repo = self.repo.get()?;\nlet remote = repo.find_remote(remote_name)?;\nlet fetch_specs = remote.refspecs(Direction::Fetch);\n```\n\nThose are `gix::refspec::RefSpec`s. To turn them back into parseable strings:\n\n```rust\nlet fetch_specs: Vec<String> = remote\n    .refspecs(Direction::Fetch)\n    .iter()\n    .map(|spec| spec.to_ref().to_bstring().to_string())\n    .collect();\n```\n\nFor your config, `meta` should yield:\n\n```text\n+refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n```\n\nThe important bit: treat this as **multiple fetch specs**, not “the fetch spec”. Git allows repeated `remote.<name>.fetch`, and `gix` returns a slice for that reason.\n\nFor [context.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/gitbutler-git/src/context.rs:59), I’d change the shape away from constructing one string. Best fix is either:\n\n```rust\ngit fetch --quiet <remote>\n```\n\nand let Git use the configured specs, or make `crate::fetch` accept `Vec<RefSpec>` and pass all configured specs. I’d pick the first unless this wrapper intentionally wants to override config.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-13T13:19:11.311Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}